A B S T R A C T
Against the backdrop of deep integration of artificial intelligence (AI) into corporate operations, this study examines
how AI adoption influences firms’ financial asset allocation decisions using panel data of Chinese listed
firms with 30,070 observations covering 2010–2023. Drawing on resource-based theory and corporate finance
perspectives, we find that AI adoption significantly increases firms’ financial asset ratios. This effect operates
through two competing mechanisms: AI enhances profitability, generating surplus funds allocated to financial
assets, while simultaneously alleviating financing constraints, with the profitability channel dominating.
Importantly, this relationship is significantly moderated by three contextual factors: firms’ digital transformation
foundations, top management teams’ technological expertise, and regional digital infrastructure quality. Heterogeneity
analyses reveal that AI’s financial impact is substantially stronger in large firms, digital economy
industries, and competitive markets. These findings contribute theoretically by extending resource-based and
corporate finance perspectives to emerging technologies, demonstrating how AI reshapes corporate resource
allocation through dual pathways contingent on organizational capabilities and environmental conditions.
Practically, firms should strengthen digital capabilities and technological leadership to maximize AI returns,
while policymakers should prioritize digital infrastructure development to amplify AI’s economic benefits.
Future research should examine these relationships across institutional contexts and employ quasi-experimental
designs to strengthen causal inference.
1. Introduction
Artificial intelligence (AI) has emerged as a transformative force
reshaping corporate strategies and resource allocation decisions (Li,
Zhong, & Tong, 2024; Zhang & Yang, 2024; Zhou, Li, Wang, Li, & Zhou,
2025). Companies across industries are increasingly integrating AI
technologies to enhance operational efficiency, strategic decision-
making, and innovation capabilities (Li, Wu, Hu, Pan, & Zhou, 2025).
Recent firm-level evidence demonstrates that investments in AI are
associated with higher growth in sales, employment, and market value,
driven primarily by improved product innovation and operational performance
(Babina, Fedyk, He, & Hodson, 2024; Dong, Xin, Liu, & Yu,
2024). These advancements suggest that AI adoption can strengthen
firms’ competitive advantages and financial outcomes (Qu & Jing, 2025;
Zhang & Piao, 2025). However, an important yet underexplored question
remains: how does AI adoption influence firms’ financial asset
allocation behavior? As firms generate efficiency gains and cost savings
from AI implementation, they face critical strategic decisions about
deploying these benefits, reinvesting in core operations, distributing to
shareholders, or accumulating financial assets. Understanding this
allocation decision has significant implications for firm growth trajectories,
innovation capacity, and broader economic development (Bahoo
et al., 2023; Dai et al., 2025; Zhou et al., 2024; Dai, 2025).
In many economies, firms have exhibited a rising propensity to
allocate resources from core productive activities toward financial investments,
a phenomenon often referred to as “corporate financialization”
(Orhangazi, 2008; Xu & Xuan, 2021). This trend has sparked
considerable debate regarding whether such reallocation supports
corporate stability and flexibility or undermines long-term productive
investment and innovation. Understanding how technological change,
particularly AI adoption, influences this trend carries both theoretical
and practical significance. Existing literature on corporate financialization
identifies multiple drivers explaining why non-financial firms
accumulate financial assets. One perspective suggests that when returns
on real sector investments are low or uncertain, firms seek alternative
revenue streams through financial investments (Demir, 2009). In China,
