as firms increasingly allocate surplus capital into financial assets amid
industrial overcapacity and economic transitions (Xu & Xuan, 2021).
Another explanation highlights that holding financial assets serves as a
strategic response to financing frictions: firms facing external financing
constraints tend to retain liquidity and short-term investments as precautionary
reserves (Bates, Kahle, & Stulz, 2009). By maintaining
buffers of financial assets, companies ensure funding availability for
future opportunities or economic downturns, thereby alleviating potential
financing constraints (Zhong & Song, 2025). While these motivations
for financialization are well-documented, little is known about
how emerging technologies like AI might fundamentally alter these
dynamics.
From a theoretical standpoint, AI adoption can influence corporate
financialization through two principal mechanisms with potentially
opposing effects. First, AI adoption may substantially improve a firm’s
core profitability and cash flow generation. According to the resource-
based view, technology capabilities serve as valuable firm resources
that enhance productivity and cost efficiency, ultimately boosting
financial performance (Xin, 2025; Durongkadej, Hu, & Wang, 2024).
Empirical studies support this perspective: firms implementing AI report
higher net profit margins and greater operational efficiency (Chen,
Esperança, & Wang, 2022). Improved profitability generates excess cash
or liquid resources, which managers might channel into financial investments
if attractive opportunities in core business operations are
limited. In this sense, AI-driven profit gains might facilitate financialization
by increasing funds available for purchasing financial assets.
Second, AI adoption may significantly affect a firm’s external financing
environment (Wang and Liu, 2025). Innovative adopters of AI could
enjoy better access to financing due to enhanced firm value and investor
confidence, or through policy support favoring technology leaders.
Recent evidence by Zhong and Song (2025) finds that AI adoption in
Chinese firms significantly relieves financing constraints, as measured
by reductions in firms’ reliance on internal funds. When external capital
becomes more accessible or internal cash flows more stable, firms have
less need to hoard precautionary liquid assets. Consequently, easing
financing constraints via AI might mitigate financialization, as companies
can confidently deploy funds in long-term projects rather than
stockpiling financial assets for safety. These two channels suggest a
complex relationship: AI adoption could simultaneously increase
financialization through profitability improvements and decrease it by
relaxing financing constraints.
Given these potentially offsetting effects, the net impact of AI on
corporate financialization becomes a critical empirical question. However,
we propose a positive net relationship based on three considerations
specific to the Chinese economic context. First, during our study
period (2010− 2023), many Chinese industries experienced overcapacity
and declining returns on physical investment (Xu & Xuan,
2021), making firms more likely to retain efficiency gains as financial
assets rather than immediately reinvesting in capacity expansion. Second,
institutional factors including capital market underdevelopment
and property rights concerns create incentives for Chinese firms to hold
liquid, easily-deployable financial assets as strategic flexibility. Third,
while AI may ease financing constraints, this likely unfolds gradually as
firms build track records and reputation, whereas profitability improvements
materialize more quickly, creating a temporal asymmetry
favoring financial asset accumulation in the short-to-medium term
captured by our panel data.
This study aims to fill this research gap by examining whether and
how AI adoption influences the financialization of non-financial firms.
Using a comprehensive panel of Chinese listed companies from 2010 to
2023 with 30,070 observations, we investigate the direct effect of firms’
AI adoption on their financial asset holdings, as well as the mediating
roles of profitability enhancement and financing constraint alleviation
in this relationship. We further consider heterogeneity in this effect by
exploring several moderators related to firms’ digital context: the degree
