Our research contributes to the literature in several important ways.
First, we bridge the gap between the technology adoption literature and
corporate finance by revealing how AI implementation shapes corporate
asset allocation decisions. While prior studies have linked technology
investments to firm growth and performance (Babina et al., 2024), we
extend this line of inquiry to the domain of financial asset management,
offering evidence on a novel determinant of corporate financialization.
Besides,we employ a longer time series capturing the recent AI boom,
explicitly test dual mediating mechanisms with formal mediation analysis
rather than inferring channels, examine three-level moderating
factors providing a comprehensive contingency framework, and employ
system GMM to address endogeneity concerns more rigorously. Second,
we unpack the mechanisms through which AI influences financialization.
By identifying profitability improvements and reduced financing
constraints as competing mediating pathways, our study sheds light on
why AI-adopting firms might hold different levels of financial assets
compared to non-adopters. This dual-path analysis provides deeper
theoretical understanding of the AI-finance nexus within firms. Third, by
analyzing moderating variables related to digital readiness at firm,
managerial, and regional levels, we highlight the contingent nature of
AI’s impact. This helps pinpoint the conditions under which AI’s influence
on financialization is amplified or dampened, which has practical
implications for managers and policymakers interested in leveraging
digital transformation while maintaining healthy real-financial asset
balances.
