2. Literature review and theoretical background
2.1. Corporate Financialization: Concept and drivers
Corporate financialization refers to the increasing allocation of
corporate resources into financial assets or activities by non-financial
firms. It is commonly quantified by the proportion of financial assets
(such as cash, marketable securities, and equity investments) to total
assets on the balance sheet. A growing body of research documents a
rising trend of financialization among non-financial enterprises in both
advanced and emerging economies (Demir, 2009; Orhangazi, 2008).
This trend reflects a strategic shift where firms prioritize financial asset
accumulation and short-term returns, sometimes at the expense of
capital expenditure in their core business operations. Several theoretical
explanations have been proposed for this phenomenon.
One explanation is grounded in the decline of productive investment
opportunities. As returns on traditional industrial projects diminish due
to market saturation or economic slowdown, firms may seek higher
yields or more stable returns in financial markets. Empirical evidence
supports this “substitution” motive: for example, Chinese firms have
increased financial investments in periods of industrial overcapacity and
shrinking profitability of core businesses, effectively shifting from “real”
to “virtual” investments (Xu & Xuan, 2021). In this view, corporate
financialization is a rational response to macroeconomic conditions and
diminishing marginal returns in the real economy.
Another important driver is the presence of financing frictions and
uncertainty. Firms with higher external financing costs or facing credit
constraints often retain liquid assets as a precaution. Holding a buffer of
cash and liquid financial instruments provides insurance against future
shocks and funding needs, consistent with the pecking-order theory that
