with tighter financing constraints exhibit a greater propensity to
accumulate cash and short-term investments (Bates et al., 2009). These
financial assets serve as liquidity reserves that can be tapped when
external capital is costly or unavailable, thereby smoothing investment
and operations. In this light, financialization can be seen as a liquidity
management strategy: it provides firms flexibility and security, albeit
potentially at the cost of forgoing some long-term investment in physical
assets. Recent studies indeed find that alleviating financing constraints
can temper firms’ incentives to hold excess financial assets. For instance,
improved access to bank credit or capital markets is associated with a
reduction in corporate cash holdings and other financial asset ratios.
Thus, the extent of corporate financialization is influenced by a trade-off
between the need for precautionary savings and the opportunities for
productive investment.
Notably, corporate financialization can have mixed implications for
firm performance and the broader economy. On one hand, moderate
levels of financial asset holdings can improve capital allocation efficiency
by allowing firms to dynamically allocate surplus funds and earn
additional income. Such financial investments might also relax future
financing constraints by generating liquid returns. On the other hand,
excessive financialization is often criticized for crowding out real investment
and innovation (Demir, 2009; Orhangazi, 2008). High financial
asset accumulation may indicate that management is prioritizing
short-term financial gains or risk-aversion over long-term growth,
which could dampen the firm’s innovation capacity and economic
growth prospects. For Chinese manufacturing firms, recent evidence
even suggests a non-linear effect: low to moderate financialization can
provide a “reservoir” of funds supporting innovation, but beyond a
threshold it begins to inhibit R&D expenditure, forming an inverted U-
shaped relationship. These findings underscore that the causes and
consequences of financialization are complex and context-dependent.
In summary, the literature indicates two key motivations behind
corporate financialization that are pertinent to our study: (1) a search for
higher returns in the face of declining productive opportunities, and (2)
a response to financing constraints and uncertainty by holding liquid
reserves. The balance between these motives can determine a firm’s
optimal financial asset holdings. We next consider how the adoption of
AI technology might alter this balance, drawing on theoretical perspectives
and emerging empirical insights.
2.2. AI adoption, firm performance, and financing environment
The diffusion of AI and related digital technologies represents a
significant technological shift with potential to impact firm behavior
broadly. The resource-based view (RBV) of the firm provides a useful
framework for understanding how AI capabilities translate into performance
outcomes. According to RBV, firms gain competitive advantage
by developing unique resources and capabilities that are valuable, rare,
and hard to imitate. AI systems, including machine learning algorithms,
intelligent automation, and big data analytics, can be regarded as
advanced organizational capabilities that improve information processing
and operational efficiency. When effectively implemented, AI
enables firms to optimize processes, reduce costs, enhance product
quality, and respond rapidly to market changes. These efficiencies
manifest in improved financial metrics. Empirical evidence is accumulating
that AI adoption boosts firm performance: for example, a recent
large-scale study finds that firms investing in AI experience significant
increases in sales growth and profitability relative to non-adopters
(Babina et al., 2024). Similarly, case studies in sectors like e-commerce
show AI-driven improvements in customer targeting and inventory
management that lead to higher revenue and profit margins
(Chen et al., 2022). In addition to raising the level of performance, AI
may also stabilize it; Lui, Lee, and Ngai (2022) report that firms with
greater AI investment see reduced volatility in sales and earnings,
indicating that AI can make operations more resilient and predictable.
