Overall, these findings suggest that AI adoption often strengthens a
firm’s financial position, yielding more robust cash flows and profits.
Beyond internal performance, AI adoption can influence a firm’s
external financing conditions. A company at the forefront of AI may be
perceived as more innovative and future-oriented, potentially
improving its valuation and attractiveness to investors and lenders. In
China, government initiatives and capital markets have increasingly
favored high-tech and digitally transforming firms, providing them with
funding advantages such as easier access to equity financing and lower-
cost bank loans. Additionally, firms that successfully deploy AI could
accumulate intellectual assets and data advantages that serve as
collateral or signals of creditworthiness. Recent research highlights a
link between AI adoption and financing constraints: Zhong and Song
(2025) show that Chinese listed companies adopting AI technologies
saw a significant reduction in their financing constraints index (a lower
SA index, per Hadlock & Pierce, 2010). This implies that those firms
either had improved access to external finance or became less dependent
on external funds (e.g. due to stronger internal cash generation), or both.
In another study, Chen, Chu, and Zhao (2024) find that AI-adopting
firms in China increased their risk-taking in investment and strategy,
with the effect being more pronounced for firms facing lower financing
constraints, suggesting that access to finance complements the risk-
mitigating benefits of AI. These pieces of evidence align with the
notion that AI can alter the financial ecosystem of the firm: by boosting
profitability and investor confidence, AI adopters may find it easier to
raise capital and thus operate with less financial stress.
It is important to recognize that implementing AI often requires
substantial upfront investment in software, hardware, and talent. Firms
with limited financial slack or financing options might struggle to adopt
AI at scale. Therefore, there could be a selection effect where firms that
are already financially stronger (or less constrained) are more likely to
invest in AI. Our analysis will account for this by controlling for firm
size, leverage, and other factors, as well as using fixed-effects to mitigate
time-invariant differences. Assuming AI adoption can be treated as at
least partially exogenous or instrumented by certain drivers (though a
full treatment of endogeneity is beyond the scope of this section), its
subsequent effects on firm financial behavior remain an open question.
2.3. Linking AI adoption to corporate Financialization
Integrating the above discussions, we propose that AI adoption has a
significant impact on corporate financialization through its effects on
profitability and financing constraints. First, consider the profitability
channel. A firm that achieves higher profits and cash flow from AI-
driven improvements has more discretionary resources at hand. Managers
then face decisions on how to utilize these funds. If the firm has
abundant profitable investment opportunities (for instance, further
expansion, R&D, or capacity building), one would expect it to reinvest
the cash into the business, which could reduce the relative share of
financial assets (since total assets grow via real investment). However, if
the firm’s growth opportunities are limited or if managers are risk-
averse, they might allocate a significant portion of the surplus funds
into financial assets. Holding financial assets can generate passive income
and offer flexibility for future investments. In many large companies,
substantial profits are often parked in short-term investments or
cash equivalents before deployment (Bates et al., 2009). Thus, higher
profitability could lead to higher financial asset ratios if immediate
reinvestment needs are met or if management prefers the liquidity and
lower risk of financial investments. In the context of AI adopters, if these
firms enjoy profit windfalls from efficiency gains, a part of those
windfalls may flow into financial portfolios (time deposits, bonds, equity
stakes, etc.), thereby increasing corporate financialization. This is
sometimes referred to as the “reservoir effect,” where excess capital is
stored in financial form. On the other hand, we acknowledge the possibility
that some AI-driven firms, especially those oriented toward
innovation, might aggressively reinvest profits into new projects (e.g.
