X. Deng and C. Qin developing more AI capabilities), which would counteract financialization.
The net effect of profitability on financial asset holding is
therefore empirical, but we lean on the precautionary and reservoir
motive literature to expect a positive link in aggregate.
Second, the financing constraint channel likely works in the opposite
direction. When AI adoption eases a firm’s financing constraints, the
firm no longer needs to retain as much liquid wealth for precautionary
motives. In other words, if a company knows it can raise debt or equity
capital relatively easily when needed (because it has proven AI strengths
and investor backing), it might choose to deploy its cash more confidently,
rather than keeping it idle in low-yield financial instruments.
This scenario would result in lower levels of financial asset holdings than
otherwise, as funds are redirected to productive uses or returned to
shareholders. Empirical evidence suggests that firms with improved
financing access reduce their cash ratios and financial investments. In
our case, AI-adopting firms that become less financially constrained
might draw down previously accumulated cash reserves or be less inclined
to build them up, thus dampening financialization. Additionally,
if AI adoption reduces earnings volatility (Lui et al., 2022; Yang, 2025),
firms may perceive less need for precautionary liquidity, further
reducing the motive to hold financial assets. Therefore, the financing
constraint relief brought by AI is expected to have a negative influence
on corporate financialization.
In summary, theory and prior findings indicate two countervailing
mechanisms: (a) AI adoption → higher profitability → higher financialization,
and (b) AI adoption → lower constraints → lower financialization.
The overall impact of AI on a firm’s financial asset ratio will
depend on the relative strength of these mechanisms. It is conceivable
that the profitability effect dominates in some contexts (leading to a net
positive effect on financialization), or conversely, the reduction in precautionary
needs dominates (leading to a net negative effect). This
nuanced outcome is an empirical matter that our study will resolve.
Beyond these average effects, we also expect heterogeneity based on
firm and regional characteristics, which we outline in our hypotheses
below.
2.4. Hypotheses development
AI Adoption and Corporate Financialization. Given the discussion
above, we first posit a direct relationship between AI implementation
and the degree of corporate financialization. Firms that actively adopt AI
technologies are likely to undergo changes in their financial profiles. On
one side, efficiency gains and cost reductions from AI can increase
profitability and generate surplus cash, part of which might be invested
in financial assets if not immediately needed for expansion. On the other
side, the improved credit standing and reduced uncertainty associated
with AI adoption can lessen the need to hold precautionary financial
buffers. Which effect prevails is ambiguous a priori. However, considering
the context of many publicly listed firms that face pressures to
show returns on idle cash, it is plausible that a significant portion of the
gains from AI adoption is temporarily placed into financial investments,
at least until compelling strategic uses arise. Indeed, early research
suggests that the application of AI technology tends to enhance the level
of financialization in enterprises (Chen et al., 2023). We thus propose
our first hypothesis:
H1. Ceteris paribus, a higher level of AI adoption in a firm is associated
with a higher degree of corporate financialization (financial assets as a
proportion of total assets).
Mediating Role of Profitability Improvement. AI-driven improvements
in firm profitability are expected to be a key mediator in the
AI–financialization relationship. As argued, AI adoption can raise net
profit margins by increasing revenue and reducing operating costs. This
improved profitability (measured, for example, by net profit to sales)
increases the pool of internal funds available to management. According
to the free cash flow theory, excess internal funds can sometimes lead to
