suboptimal uses if not disciplined, one such use can be accumulating
financial investments or cash beyond what is needed. Even absent
agency problems, prudent management may choose to hold a portion of
newfound profits in liquid form to maintain flexibility. Therefore, we
expect that AI adoption contributes to higher financial asset holdings
partly through its positive impact on profitability. Formally:
H2. The positive effect of AI adoption on corporate financialization is
mediated by an improvement in firm profitability. (AI adoption →
higher profitability → higher financialization.)
Mediating Role of Financing Constraint Alleviation. The second
mediating mechanism relates to the firm’s financing constraints. As
discussed, firms adopting AI may experience relaxed financing frictions
due to better performance signals and greater investor confidence
(Zhong & Song, 2025). We measure financing constraints via the SA
index (size-age index from Hadlock & Pierce, 2010), where a lower
value indicates easier access to finance. AI adoption is hypothesized to
reduce this index. When financing constraints are alleviated, the firm’s
reliance on self-financing and precautionary cash is reduced, which
should logically lead to a decrease in financial asset holdings relative to
total assets. This is because the firm can deploy funds more freely into
long-term investments or pay them out, knowing that external finance is
attainable if needed. We thus expect a negative mediation effect through
financing constraints:
H3. AI adoption alleviates firms’ financing constraints, which in turn
reduces the level of corporate financialization. (AI adoption → lower
financing constraints → lower financialization.)
It should be noted that H2 and H3 describe two competing pathways.
In our empirical analysis, we will test the significance of each mediation
path to understand their relative magnitudes. It is possible that both
operate simultaneously, partially offsetting each other. For instance, AI
might increase financialization through profitability (supporting H2)
while also decreasing it through lowered constraints (supporting H3). A
finding that H2 dominates would align with an overall positive effect of
AI on financialization (consistent with H1), whereas a stronger H3 could
dampen or even overturn the direct effect.
Moderating Role of Digital Transformation Foundation. Not all firms
benefit equally from AI adoption; the existing digital infrastructure and
capabilities of a firm can moderate the outcomes. We define a firm’s
digital transformation foundation (DIG) as the proportion of intangible
assets related to digital technology (software, data platforms, etc.) in its
total intangible assets. A higher DIG indicates that the firm has already
invested in digital resources and is more digitally mature. Such a
foundation likely complements AI implementation – a digitally mature
firm can integrate AI tools more effectively into its operations, yielding
greater performance improvements. Consequently, we expect that in
firms with a strong digital foundation, the effects of AI adoption (on
profitability and on easing finance frictions) are amplified. This means
the eventual impact on financialization could also be stronger. If H1
holds (AI increases financialization), a strong digital base would
magnify that increase by enabling AI to generate even more surplus
funds or returns. Alternatively, if AI mainly reduces precautionary motives,
a strong digital base might amplify that reduction. In either case,
the interaction is expected to be significant. We hypothesize:
H4. The firm’s digital transformation foundation positively moderates
the effect of AI adoption on corporate financialization. The influence of
AI on financialization is stronger for firms with greater digital intangible
asset bases.
Moderating Role of Top Management Team’s Technology Cognition.
Effective adoption of AI often requires visionary leadership and understanding
at the top management level. We consider the technology
cognition of the top management team (TMTECH) as an ordinal indicator
of digital expertise among executives. A higher TMTECH score
(where, for example, 3 indicates a CEO or Chair with tech background)
