X. Deng and C. Qin signals that leadership is technologically savvy. Such leaders are more
likely to successfully implement AI initiatives and also to strategically
manage the resulting financial outcomes. A tech-oriented management
might, for instance, be more inclined to reinvest AI-generated earnings
into further tech innovation rather than purely financial investments, or
vice versa, they might better recognize lucrative fintech opportunities
for excess cash. Overall, we posit that management’s tech cognition will
intensify the impact (directionally) of AI on financialization. If AI tends
to increase financialization, tech-savvy managers will enable an even
greater increase by fully capitalizing on AI-related financial gains.
Conversely, they might also make more efficient use of slack, possibly
tempering pure financial hoarding. On balance, we expect an enhancing
effect on whatever direction AI pushes financialization. Formally:
H5. The positive relationship between AI adoption and corporate
financialization (H1) is stronger when the top management team has
higher technology cognition. In other words, firms led by tech-savvy
management exhibit a more pronounced change in financial asset
holdings in response to AI adoption.
Moderating Role of Regional Digital Infrastructure. Finally, the
broader environment in which a firm operates can shape the returns to
its AI investments. We consider the regional digital infrastructure (INF),
measured by the emphasis on new digital infrastructure in the local
government’s reports (frequency of keywords indicating digital infrastructure
development). Regions with better digital infrastructure (such
as widespread high-speed internet, data centers, 5G networks, smart city
initiatives) provide a supportive context for companies to implement AI
solutions effectively. In such regions, AI adoption by firms is likely to
yield greater performance benefits due to external spillovers and
network effects (e.g., availability of skilled workforce, suppliers, and
complementary services). This should again magnify the impact of AI on
firm financial outcomes. We hypothesize a similar moderating effect at
the regional level:
H6. The effect of AI adoption on corporate financialization is more
pronounced for firms located in regions with more advanced digital
infrastructure. A conducive digital environment strengthens the link
between AI implementation and firms’ financial asset allocation
changes.
By testing H4, H5, and H6, we aim to paint a clearer picture of the
contexts under which AI adoption most strongly affects financialization.
These moderators will be examined through interaction terms in our
regression models, as described in the methodology.
3. Methodology
3.1. Data and sample
We construct a panel dataset of Chinese A-share listed non-financial
companies from 2010 to 2023 to empirically test the above hypotheses.
The initial sample is drawn from financial statement data and supplemental
disclosures available in the China Stock Market & Accounting
Research (CSMAR) and China Research Data Services (CNRDS) databases.
We focus on the 2010–2023 period, during which AI-related investments
by firms became increasingly prevalent and detailed data on
such investments can be obtained from annual report notes. The sample
consists of 4719 firms and a total of 30,070 firm-year observations after
applying the following filtering criteria for data reliability and
consistency:
•We exclude firms with special treatment status (ST, *ST) or particular
transfer (PT) status, as these companies are under financial
distress or restructuring, which could skew their financial asset
holdings and technology investment behavior.
•We exclude firms in the financial industry (such as banks, insurers,
securities companies) because their asset structures and regulatory
