environments are entirely different (financial assets are part of core
operations for them, not an indicator of “financialization” in the
same sense).
•We drop any firm-year observations with missing values for key
variables used in our analysis (AI investment measures, financial
assets, control variables, etc.), ensuring a balanced panel where
possible.
•All continuous variables are winsorized at the 1 % level at both tails
to mitigate the influence of outliers. This standard procedure prevents
extreme values from unduly affecting the regression results,
particularly pertinent given the skewness often observed in financial
ratios.
•For our main independent variable (AI adoption level), we apply a
data transformation to address high skewness and heteroscedasticity.
Specifically, because the AI adoption proxy (explained below) exhibits
a large standard deviation across firms, we add 1 to the raw
measure, take the natural logarithm, and then divide by 10. This log-
scaling smooths extreme differences and helps linearize the relationship
without altering the ordinal information (a similar approach
is taken in prior literature where investment variables are highly
skewed).
After these preprocessing steps, our final sample is a panel well-
suited for fixed-effects regression analysis. The panel structure allows
us to control for unobserved firm-specific factors (via firm fixed effects)
and for macroeconomic or systemic shocks common to all firms in a
given year (via year fixed effects). By leveraging within-firm variation
over time, we aim to isolate the impact of changes in AI adoption on
changes in financialization, while holding constant time-invariant firm
characteristics.
3.2. Variable definitions and measurement
Corporate Financialization (FIN). The dependent variable is the
degree of corporate financialization, denoted as FIN, measured as the
proportion of a firm’s financial assets to its total assets. Financial assets
are defined to include cash and cash equivalents, short-term investments
in securities (stocks, bonds, wealth management products), other receivable
investments, and any other financial asset items reported on the
balance sheet. This ratio captures the extent to which a firm’s assets are
tied up in financial forms as opposed to real economy assets (like inventory,
fixed assets, etc.). A higher FIN indicates a greater orientation
toward financial holdings. In robustness checks, we also construct an
alternative measure FIN_dum, a dummy variable equal to 1 if the firm
holds any significant financial assets (e.g., non-zero holdings in particular
categories like trading securities or wealth management products)
and 0 otherwise. While most listed firms do hold some financial assets,
this dummy is more relevant when focusing on the extensive margin of
financialization (whether to financialize or not). Our main analysis,
however, concentrates on the continuous ratio FIN.
AI Adoption (AI). The primary independent variable is the firm’s AI
adoption level (AI). Following recent literature in the Chinese context,
we proxy AI adoption by a firm using information from annual report
notes about investments in intelligent machinery and equipment. Specifically,
we take the total value of purchases of machinery and equipment
related to automation or AI (as disclosed in the fixed asset notes)
and scale it by the number of employees. This per-employee machinery
investment serves as a proxy for the intensity of AI and automation
technology adoption in the firm’s operations. The data for this is gathered
via text analysis of financial statement footnotes, using keywords to
identify AI-related equipment (e.g., industrial robots, smart
manufacturing systems). The ratio is then log-transformed (log(1 +
value/employee)/10) as noted above. A larger value of AI indicates a
higher degree of AI integration in the firm relative to its labor size,
reflecting more extensive adoption of AI tools and machinery. We
acknowledge that this is an indirect measure – it captures automation
