Mediators: We examine two mediating variables. The first is Profitability
Improvement (NetProfit), measured as the net profit divided by
operating revenue (net profit margin). This captures the firm’s profit
efficiency – how much profit is generated per unit of sales – and reflects
improvements in cost management or value addition potentially
brought by AI. We denote this ratio by NetProfit and expect AI adoption
to increase it. The second mediator is Financing Constraint (FC). To
measure a firm’s financing constraints, we use the SA index developed
by Hadlock and Pierce (2010). This index is constructed as:
SA=− 0.737 ×Size +0.043 ×Size2
− 0.040 ×Age,
where Size is the natural log of total assets (in 2009 RMB millions) and
Age is the firm’s age (years since establishment). The SA index is a
parsimonious measure where higher values indicate greater financial
constraint (typically smaller, younger firms). We compute this index for
each firm-year and use it as our FC variable. A reduction in FC (a lower
SA value) implies an alleviation of financing constraints. Notably, this
measure relies only on exogenous or slow-moving firm traits (size and
age) and avoids direct inclusion of potentially endogenous financial
variables, making it suitable for avoiding certain endogeneity concerns
(Hadlock & Pierce, 2010). We expect AI adoption to correlate with a
decrease in FC, reflecting easier financing.
Moderators: Three moderator variables are considered, each interacting
with AI adoption in the models. Digital Transformation Foundation
(DIG) is measured as the proportion of intangible assets related to
digital technology to total intangible assets. From firms’ annual reports,
we identify the year-end carrying value of intangible assets that are
digital in nature (such as software platforms, proprietary information
systems, databases, etc.) and divide it by total intangible assets. This
ratio, denoted DIG, indicates how much of the firm’s intangible capital is
invested in digital technology, serving as a proxy for the firm’s baseline
digital capability. Top Management Team’s Technology Cognition
(TMTECH) is an index reflecting the presence of tech expertise in the top
management team (TMT). We code TMTECH on a scale of 0 to 3: a value
of 0 if the firm has no senior executives with a background in digital
technology, 1 if at least one TMT member has tech experience or education,
2 if such a tech-experienced member also sits on the board of
directors, and 3 if the firm’s CEO or board chair themselves has a strong
digital tech background (making them a “digital leader”). This ordinal
variable TMTECH captures increasing levels of technological orientation
in leadership. Finally, Regional Digital Infrastructure (INF) measures the
external digital environment. For each firm-year, we proxy INF by
analyzing the city-level government work report for the frequency of
terms related to “new digital infrastructure” (e.g., mentions of data
