4.4.2. Addressing endogeneity concerns
A potential concern in our analysis is endogeneity arising from
reverse causality, omitted variable bias, or simultaneity. Specifically,
firms with stronger financial positions or greater financial asset holdings
may possess more resources to invest in expensive AI technologies,
creating a reverse causal pathway from financialization to AI adoption
rather than the hypothesized direction. Additionally, unobserved firm
characteristics such as managerial quality, organizational culture, or
strategic orientation may simultaneously influence both AI adoption
decisions and financial asset allocation strategies, leading to omitted
variable bias. Furthermore, AI adoption and financialization decisions
may be jointly determined as part of broader corporate strategy, introducing
simultaneity bias. To address these endogeneity concerns
comprehensively, we employ three distinct approaches: instrumental
variable estimation, propensity score matching, and the Heckman two-
stage selection model.
Instrumental Variable Approach. We first employ a two-stage least
squares (2SLS) regression using the one-period lagged value of AI
adoption as an instrument. The lagged AI adoption (L.lnAI) serves as a
valid instrument for several theoretical and empirical reasons. First, it
satisfies the relevance condition: past AI investment strongly predicts
current AI adoption due to the cumulative and path-dependent nature of
technology implementation. Firms that invested in AI in the previous
period are highly likely to continue and expand their AI initiatives, as AI
deployment involves substantial learning curves, complementary investments
