profitability, measured as net profit margin (NetProfit). Column 1 presents
the first-stage regression examining whether AI adoption influences
firm profitability. The coefficient on AI adoption (lnAI) is 0.006
and highly significant (t = 2.824, p < 0.01), indicating that firms
investing more heavily in AI technologies achieve higher net profit
margins. This finding aligns with the resource-based view and existing
empirical evidence: AI technologies enhance productivity by optimizing
operations, improving decision quality, reducing costs, and enabling
better resource allocation (Chen et al., 2022). The economic magnitude
suggests that a one standard deviation increase in AI adoption is associated
with approximately a 0.29 percentage point increase in net profit
margin, representing meaningful profitability gains.Among control
variables in column 1, return on equity (ROE) shows an exceptionally
strong positive relationship with net profit margin (coefficient =0.698,
t =50.261, p < 0.001), which is unsurprising given both measures
