4.6. Moderating effects of digital environment and technology
Having established that AI adoption positively influences corporate
financialization through profitability enhancement and financing
constraint alleviation, we now examine the boundary conditions of this
relationship. Not all firms benefit equally from AI adoption; the effectiveness
of AI in reshaping financial asset allocation likely depends on
complementary organizational capabilities and environmental conditions.
We investigate three moderating factors operating at different
levels: firm-level digital transformation foundation, managerial-level
top management team technological cognition, and regional-level digital
infrastructure. These analyses test Hypotheses 4, 5, and 6, respectively,
and provide insights into when and where AI adoption most
strongly influences corporate financialization.
Digital Transformation Foundation. Table 15 examines whether a
firm’s existing digital transformation foundation moderates the AI-
financialization relationship. We measure digital transformation foundation
(DIG) as the proportion of intangible assets related to digital
technology relative to total intangible assets, reflecting the firm’s
baseline digital capability and infrastructure. Column 1 presents a model
including both AI adoption and DIG as main effects. The coefficient on
AI remains positive and significant (coefficient =0.006, t =3.463, p <
0.01), consistent with baseline findings. The coefficient on DIG itself is
negative but statistically insignificant (coefficient = − 0.004, t =
− 0.768), suggesting that digital foundation alone does not directly
predict financialization levels after controlling for other factors.
Column 2 introduces the critical interaction term between AI adoption
and digital foundation (DIG ×lnAI). The interaction coefficient is
positive and highly significant (coefficient =0.024, t =3.056, p <0.01),
providing strong support for Hypothesis 4. This positive interaction indicates
that the effect of AI adoption on financialization is significantly
amplified in firms with stronger digital transformation foundations. In
economic terms, firms that have already invested substantially in digital
infrastructure, software platforms, data management systems, and
related intangible assets derive greater financial benefits from AI
adoption than firms with weaker digital foundations. The main effect of
AI remains significant (coefficient =0.006, t =3.494, p <0.01), while
the DIG main effect becomes positive though remains insignificant
(coefficient = 0.006, t = 0.990).This moderating effect aligns with
theories of technological complementarity and absorptive capacity. AI
technologies do not operate in isolation but require supporting digital
infrastructure to function effectively. Firms with robust digital foundations
possess the necessary data systems, connectivity, and digital skills
that enable AI tools to be implemented seamlessly and deliver maximum
value. For instance, machine learning algorithms require quality data,
which depends on existing data collection and management systems. AI-
driven analytics need integration with enterprise resource planning
systems and business intelligence platforms. Cloud-based AI applications
demand adequate network infrastructure and cybersecurity capabilities.
Firms lacking these complementary digital assets struggle to
fully exploit AI’s potential, resulting in weaker impacts on performance
and consequently on financial outcomes.
The finding that digital foundation moderates rather than directly
affects financialization is theoretically informative. It suggests that
digital capabilities matter primarily in conjunction with AI adoption
rather than independently. Simply possessing digital infrastructure
without deploying advanced AI applications does not substantially alter
financial asset strategies. However, when AI is introduced into an
already digitally mature organization, a synergistic effect emerges that
magnifies AI’s impact on generating surplus funds and improving
financial positions, ultimately leading to greater financialization. This
highlights the importance of sequential technology investments: firms
should build digital foundations before or concurrent with AI adoption
to maximize returns.
