The findings align with and extend theories of technological
complementarity and dynamic capabilities (Teece, 2007). AI represents
a general-purpose technology whose productivity gains emerge only
when combined with appropriate organizational capabilities and infrastructure.
Firms with strong digital foundations, technologically savvy
leadership, and favorable regional environments can effectively integrate
AI into operations, leading to substantial performance improvements
and consequent increases in financial asset holdings. In contrast,
firms lacking these complementary factors struggle to extract value from
AI investments, resulting in minimal or no effects on financialization.
From a practical standpoint, these results provide actionable guidance
for managers and policymakers. Managers considering AI adoption
should first assess and strengthen their organizations’ digital readiness,
cultivate technological expertise in leadership teams, and consider
location decisions in relation to regional digital infrastructure. Piecemeal
AI adoption without these complementary investments is unlikely
to yield maximum returns. Policymakers seeking to promote AI-driven
economic growth should invest in public digital infrastructure, support
executive education programs enhancing technological literacy,
and create regional innovation ecosystems that provide supportive environments
for AI adoption. The substantial interaction effects documented
here suggest that such complementary investments could
generate significant returns by enabling firms to fully capture AI’s
transformative potential.
