5. Conclusion
5.1. Summary of key findings
This study provides comprehensive empirical evidence on how
artificial intelligence adoption influences corporate financial asset
allocation decisions. Using panel data of Chinese listed firms with
30,070 observations covering 2010 to 2023, we establish several key
findings that advance understanding of the AI-financialization nexus.
First, we find robust evidence that AI adoption significantly increases
corporate financial asset holdings. This positive relationship persists
across multiple model specifications, alternative measures, and rigorous
endogeneity tests including instrumental variable estimation, propensity
score matching, and Heckman selection models. The economic
magnitude is substantial: AI adoption explains meaningful variation in
financial asset ratios beyond traditional determinants, suggesting that
technological innovation has become an important driver of corporate
financial strategies.
Second, we identify and empirically validate two competing mediating
mechanisms through which AI influences financialization. AI
adoption enhances firm profitability by improving operational efficiency,
decision quality, and competitive positioning, generating surplus
internal funds that flow into financial asset accumulation. This profitability
channel accounts for approximately 14 % of the total AI effect.
Simultaneously, AI adoption alleviates financing constraints by
improving firm performance signals, enhancing creditworthiness, and
increasing investor confidence, which affects financial asset holdings
through improved financial capacity. This financing constraint channel
contributes approximately 5 % of the total effect. The dominance of the
profitability mechanism over the financing constraint mechanism explains
the net positive impact of AI on financialization, supporting our
theoretical framework that surplus generation outweighs reduced precautionary
motives in determining financial asset strategies.
Third, we demonstrate that AI’s impact on financialization is highly
context-dependent, contingent on complementary capabilities and
environmental conditions at multiple levels. At the firm level, organizations
with stronger digital transformation foundations experience
significantly amplified AI effects, reflecting technological complementarities
where AI requires supporting digital infrastructure to deliver
maximum value. At the managerial level, top management teams with
greater technological cognition more effectively leverage AI investments,
resulting in stronger financialization impacts through better
implementation and strategic deployment of AI-generated resources. At
the regional level, superior digital infrastructure dramatically enhances
AI’s effectiveness, with the interaction magnitude suggesting that
environmental conditions may be particularly powerful enablers of AI
value realization.
Fourth, heterogeneity analyses reveal that AI-driven financialization
effects vary systematically across organizational and market contexts.
Large firms exhibit substantially stronger relationships between AI
adoption and financial asset holdings compared to smaller firms,
reflecting resource advantages, scale economies, and implementation
capabilities. Firms in digital economy industries show pronounced AI-
financialization relationships while traditional industry firms exhibit
minimal effects, indicating that technological alignment and existing
digital capabilities shape AI’s financial implications. Companies operating
in competitive markets demonstrate stronger AI effects than those
in less competitive environments, suggesting that competitive pressure
intensifies both AI deployment urgency and the strategic value of AI-
generated financial flexibility.
Collectively, these findings paint a nuanced picture of how emerging
technologies reshape corporate finance. AI adoption is neither uniformly
beneficial nor operates through simple direct pathways. Rather, its influence
on financial asset allocation emerges through multiple mechanisms,
depends critically on complementary organizational and
environmental factors, and varies substantially across firm and industry
