simplistic technology adoption models toward richer frameworks
recognizing contingencies and complementarities.
5.2. Theoretical implications
This research makes several important theoretical contributions that
advance multiple literature streams. First, we extend the resource-based
view (RBV) by demonstrating that AI capabilities function as strategic
resources with implications beyond operational performance to include
financial strategy outcomes. While traditional RBV applications focus on
how valuable, rare, and inimitable resources generate competitive advantages,
we show that these advantages manifest not only in market
performance but also in financial asset allocation decisions. AI capabilities
represent knowledge-based resources that enhance organizational
information processing, decision-making efficiency, and adaptive
capacity. Our findings that AI’s value depends on complementary resources
including digital infrastructure, managerial cognition, and
regional ecosystems directly support and extend RBV’s emphasis on
resource complementarities and bundles. This integration of RBV with
corporate finance contributes to both fields by revealing how strategic
resources shape financial structures beyond traditional capital structure
considerations.
Second, we contribute to corporate finance theory by identifying
technological innovation as a novel determinant of financial asset
accumulation, expanding beyond conventional drivers emphasized in
existing literature. Prior research focuses primarily on declining investment
opportunities in real sectors (Demir, 2009), financing frictions,
and agency problems (Jensen, 1986) as explanations for corporate
financialization. We introduce AI adoption as an additional mechanism
operating through distinct pathways. Our dual-mediation framework
reconciles and integrates two foundational finance theories: free cash
flow theory and pecking order theory. AI generates surplus cash flows
consistent with the view that firms may allocate to financial investments
when agency problems or limited growth opportunities constrain productive
deployment. Simultaneously, AI alleviates information asymmetries
and financing constraints, affecting financial asset decisions
through improved external financing access. By demonstrating that both
mechanisms operate concurrently with differential magnitudes, we
provide a more complete theoretical account of how technology-driven
financial performance improvements translate into asset allocation
outcomes.
Third, our study advances technology management and innovation
literature by empirically validating contingency perspectives on AI
value realization. We provide evidence supporting theories of technological
complementarity and general-purpose technology diffusion in
the specific context of AI adoption. The significant three-level moderating
effects across firm digital foundations, managerial cognition, and
regional infrastructure demonstrate that AI benefits emerge only when
embedded in supportive organizational and environmental contexts.
This finding helps explain persistent productivity paradoxes and heterogeneous
AI returns documented in prior research: variation in complementary
investments and contextual conditions generates differential
outcomes even when firms nominally adopt similar AI technologies. Our
framework integrating internal capabilities, leadership characteristics,
and external infrastructure provides a template for future research
examining conditions under which emerging technologies deliver
promised benefits.
Fourth, we contribute methodologically by employing a comprehensive
empirical approach addressing multiple endogeneity concerns
and testing complex mediation and moderation relationships simultaneously.
Our triangulation across instrumental variables, propensity
score matching, and selection models provides robust causal evidence
strengthening confidence in findings. The formal mediation tests with
Sobel statistics and bootstrap confidence intervals offer rigorous validation
of theoretical mechanisms. The multi-level moderation analyses
