demonstrate how to examine contingencies operating at different
organizational levels within a unified framework. This methodological
rigor sets standards for future empirical research on technology-finance
relationships.
Finally, our findings speak to emerging debates about financialization
consequences in the context of technological change. While extensive
literature debates whether corporate financialization represents
efficient capital allocation or problematic diversion from productive
investment (Orhangazi, 2008), we show that technological innovation
introduces additional complexity. AI-driven financialization may differ
fundamentally from financialization driven by declining real sector
opportunities or short-term financial market pressures. When financialization
results from technology-enhanced profitability generating
legitimate surplus resources, normative assessments may differ from
cases where financialization reflects rent-seeking or strategic stagnation.
Our research suggests that the welfare implications of financialization
cannot be evaluated independently of its underlying drivers, opening
avenues for future theoretical development distinguishing between
productive and unproductive forms of financial asset accumulation.
5.3. Managerial implications
Our findings offer actionable insights for multiple stakeholder groups
including corporate managers, investors, and policymakers, with implications
for strategic decision-making, investment evaluation, and
policy design.
Implications for Corporate Managers. Executives should recognize AI
adoption as a strategic initiative with significant financial implications
extending beyond operational improvements. Our evidence demonstrates
that AI investments generate not only efficiency gains and
competitive advantages but also reshape corporate financial profiles by
increasing financial asset holdings. Managers should therefore integrate
AI strategy with financial planning, anticipating that successful AI
implementation will generate surplus resources requiring strategic
allocation decisions. Rather than viewing AI purely as an operational
technology, leadership should understand its role in enhancing financial
flexibility and resource availability.
However, managers must also recognize that capturing AI’s full
financial benefits requires complementary investments and capabilities.
Organizations should assess and strengthen their digital transformation
foundations before or concurrent with AI adoption, ensuring adequate
data infrastructure, information systems, and digital skill bases exist to
support AI implementation. Piecemeal AI investments without supporting
digital capabilities are unlikely to yield maximum returns.
Additionally, firms should invest in developing technological cognition
at the leadership level through executive education, strategic hires
bringing technology expertise to top management teams, and cultivation
of digital literacy across the organization. Our findings suggest that
technology-oriented leadership significantly amplifies AI’s financial
impacts, making human capital development in technological domains a
high-priority complement to AI technology investments.
Furthermore, managers should carefully evaluate organizational and
environmental contexts when formulating AI strategies. Large firms,
those in digital economy sectors, and companies facing competitive
pressure appear particularly well-positioned to benefit financially from
AI adoption. Smaller firms in traditional industries may need to adjust
expectations, pursue focused AI applications aligned with specific capabilities,
or consider collaborative approaches pooling resources with
partners to overcome scale and capability disadvantages. Location decisions
should also consider regional digital infrastructure quality, as our
evidence suggests environmental factors substantially moderate AI
benefits. Firms in regions with limited digital infrastructure may need to
invest more heavily in self-sufficient technological capabilities or
engage with policymakers to improve local conditions.
Implications for Investors and Financial Analysts. Our findings provide
investors with new frameworks for evaluating corporate AI
