Additionally, investors should consider AI adoption patterns when
evaluating financial asset holdings. Increases in financial assets among
AI-adopting firms may reflect prudent management of technology-
generated surpluses rather than concerning over-financialization.
Context matters: AI-driven financial asset accumulation in firms with
strong growth prospects and continued innovation investment likely
differs from financially motivated asset accumulation by stagnant firms
avoiding productive investment. Investors should thus assess whether
financial asset increases accompany or substitute for innovation and real
investment when interpreting corporate strategies.
Implications for Policymakers. Government officials and regulators
should view digital infrastructure as critical public goods warranting
substantial investment. Our findings demonstrate that regional digital
infrastructure dramatically amplifies firm-level AI returns, suggesting
that public infrastructure provision generates significant positive externalities
for private sector innovation and performance. Policies
should prioritize expanding broadband access, supporting data center
development, promoting 5G network deployment, and fostering digital
technology service ecosystems. These investments create enabling environments
allowing firms to maximize AI adoption benefits, ultimately
supporting economic growth, productivity improvements, and competitive
advantages.
Beyond infrastructure, policymakers should consider targeted support
for AI adoption, particularly for firms facing resource constraints or
operating in less digitally intensive sectors. Subsidies, tax incentives,
low-cost financing, and technical assistance programs could help smaller
firms and traditional industry companies overcome barriers to AI
implementation, reducing disparities in technology access and benefits.
However, such support should be coupled with requirements or incentives
for complementary investments in digital foundations and
human capital development, ensuring that subsidized AI adoption occurs
in contexts supporting successful implementation.
Educational and workforce development policies should emphasize
technological literacy and digital skills at all levels, from basic digital
competence in the general workforce to advanced technical capabilities
among specialists and strategic technology understanding among business
leaders. Our finding that managerial technological cognition
significantly moderates AI benefits underscores the importance of executive
education programs, university curricula emphasizing technology
management, and professional development opportunities helping
current leaders develop digital fluency. Broader workforce digital skill
development ensures adequate talent supply supporting widespread AI
adoption across industries.
Finally, policymakers should monitor AI-driven financialization
patterns to ensure they reflect productive resource allocation rather than
problematic diversion from real economic activities. While our evidence
suggests AI-driven financial asset accumulation stems from legitimate
surplus generation, regulators should remain vigilant for excessive
financialization that might undermine long-term productive investment,
innovation capacity, or employment. Balanced policies encouraging AI
adoption while maintaining incentives for continued real sector investment
and innovation can help optimize economic outcomes from
technological transformation.
