5.4. Limitations and future research directions
Despite its contributions, this study has important limitations that
suggest avenues for future research. First, measurement and methodological
challenges constrain our ability to draw definitive conclusions.
Our AI adoption proxies, while grounded in objective financial data,
capture AI-related capital expenditures rather than actual deployment
intensity, utilization patterns, or value generation from AI systems.
Firms may purchase AI equipment or software without effectively
implementing or integrating it into operations, introducing measurement
error that likely attenuates estimated effects toward zero, implying
our findings may understate true relationships. Similarly, our dependent
variable measuring financial assets as a proportion of total assets aggregates
diverse asset types including operational cash, short-term investments,
and longer-term financial holdings. This broad definition
may conflate precautionary liquidity management with strategic
financial investment, limiting our ability to distinguish between
different motives for financial asset accumulation.
Despite our multiple robustness checks including instrumental variables,
propensity score matching, and Heckman selection models
addressing different endogeneity sources, causal identification challenges
persist. Reverse causality remains plausible: financially strong
firms with substantial financial assets may possess greater capacity to
undertake expensive AI investments, creating feedback loops our models
cannot fully disentangle. Omitted variables such as unobserved managerial
quality, organizational culture, or strategic orientation may
simultaneously influence AI adoption decisions and financial asset
strategies.
Future research should address these limitations through several
approaches. Studies should leverage richer firm-level data on AI projects,
AI talent composition, AI-generated outputs, or AI system utilization
metrics to measure adoption more accurately. Financial assets
should be disaggregated into subcategories such as cash and equivalents,
trading securities, available-for-sale investments, and equity stakes in
other firms, examining whether AI adoption affects these components
differentially. Research should exploit quasi-natural experiments such
as exogenous shocks to AI adoption costs, regional AI policy variations,
or technological breakthroughs enabling difference-in-differences or
regression discontinuity designs that strengthen causal inference.
Mixed-methods approaches combining econometric analysis with
qualitative case evidence would provide more comprehensive understanding
of how AI causally affects financial strategies.
Future research should conduct cross-country comparative studies
examining whether our findings replicate in diverse institutional contexts.
Multi-country samples could test whether the AI-financialization
relationship is universal or context-specific, identifying institutional
factors that amplify or dampen effects. Country-specific studies in
developed economies, other emerging markets, or frontier markets
would reveal how economic development levels, financial market sophistication,
and regulatory frameworks shape AI’s financial implications.
Longer time horizons using extended panels or longitudinal
tracking of cohorts over decades could illuminate dynamic patterns and
long-term consequences. Research should examine downstream outcomes
including how AI-adopting firms with higher financial assets
subsequently perform on innovation output, R&D investment, employment
growth, productivity improvements, and long-term market value
compared to AI adopters maintaining lower financial asset ratios. Such
analyses would reveal whether AI-driven financialization supports or
hinders firms’ real economic contributions.
Finally, our study identifies that substantial portions of AI’s total
effect on financialization operate through unmeasured mechanisms
beyond profitability and financing constraints. Future research should
investigate additional mediating pathways including AI’s effects on risk
management capabilities, information processing efficiency, organizational
learning, strategic flexibility, and competitive positioning. Qualitative
research exploring managers’ decision-making processes
19
X. Deng and C. Qin regarding AI-generated resources could uncover mechanisms not easily
captured in quantitative models. Attention to behavioral factors, organizational
routines, and institutional pressures shaping financial asset
allocation decisions would enrich understanding of the AI-
financialization relationship’s microfoundations.
In conclusion, while this study advances knowledge significantly,
substantial opportunities remain for deeper exploration of how
emerging technologies reshape corporate finance. Future research
addressing these limitations through improved measurement, stronger
causal designs, cross-context comparisons, long-term analyses, and
investigation of additional mechanisms will further illuminate the
complex interplay between technological innovation and financial
strategy in modern corporations.
